00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:12,000
It's actually a joy to be here in Skye. Your brother ended up on a Greek island, you ended up on a Hebridean island. Who do you think won?

2
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:20,000
Oh, my brother. He was a sensible one. I could have made that decision for a long time ago.

3
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:33,000
Well, it feels extraordinary as a place. It feels like you're the end of the world. You could have ended up anywhere. You know, Trondlass and Oxford or whatever. Why?

4
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:43,000
I don't think I'd ever have ended up living in a city. I find it very important to be close to a wild and natural scene.

5
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:59,000
My brother and I shared a lot. When we were young, we just said there were two great places to live. One of them is the Scottish islands and the other is the Greek islands. He's ended up on the Greek islands and I've ended up in the Scottish islands.

6
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:02,000
You can live vicariously.

7
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:20,000
I came to see you eight years ago or so for the same project where I'd speak to influential and compelling thinkers about a question that they think you should be asking yourselves.

8
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:41,000
The question you offered them was, what is my culture preventing me from seeing? Since then, you've written a massive tome, which I have here, the matter with things. You've produced a huge amount. Is that still the question that you think we do well to start considering a bit more closely?

9
00:01:41,000 --> 00:02:00,000
I think it's a very important question, because if you don't know what it is that's missing from your life, you won't know how to lead your life so as to rediscover the things that you no longer see.

10
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:12,000
So not knowing what it is you don't know is the fatal problem. Not knowing is fine, but knowing that you don't know is a very good position and exploring that.

11
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:24,000
But in our culture, we're encouraged to think that increasingly we know it all, that we've got it all worked out and we're organising life according to lines that we have set up.

12
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:43,000
And we're not aware of what it is that's gone missing. I think people of my age, I'm 71, see things having disappeared from life during their lifetime.

13
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:57,000
And I don't know quite how young people would know that these things were missing really, unless we were able to discuss them and open eyes to them.

14
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:09,000
So I wonder if we could begin by talking about what we, well maybe what you mean by seeing, attention as a moral act is kind of a shorthand for much of your work.

15
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:13,000
When you talk about what we're seeing, are you talking about what we're paying attention to?

16
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:20,000
I am, I'm not talking about visual sight, I'm talking about the things that we recognise and understand.

17
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:32,000
And though sight is a very important and powerful sense with which we get to know things in the world, it's not really what I'm talking about.

18
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:41,000
So what is it, I suppose, what is it that you think we are seeing and not seeing?

19
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:48,000
What are we paying attention to, to the exclusion of other things? What would be, say, examples of that?

20
00:03:49,000 --> 00:04:03,000
Well, I think that we've been led to adopt and become enslaved by a certain way of looking at the world, which is mechanistic and reductionist.

21
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:24,000
And with that, a sense of values, a sense of purpose, a sense of there being something wonderful or inspiring and perhaps sacred in the world has gone missing.

22
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:37,000
And it's very sad that, it's not just my impression, but the research shows that a very large majority of young people over 80% think that their life is meaningless.

23
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:55,000
It may be that we've developed all kinds of gadgetry and technology, but nothing can really replace the sense of meaning by sheer material wherewithal.

24
00:04:56,000 --> 00:05:02,000
So we value, we seem to be valuing what the left hemisphere values.

25
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:08,000
The left hemisphere is essentially in the service of utility.

26
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:14,000
The reason we have two hemispheres, and it's not just us, but all the creatures that we know have brains have two hemispheres.

27
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:19,000
And the difference is that they pay attention to the world in different ways.

28
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:24,000
And the left hemisphere's attention is in the service of utility.

29
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:31,000
It's a very narrowly targeted attention to something that's already known to be of value when it goes and gets it.

30
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:38,000
Now that is essentially how we look at what do we need, what would we like, what would make us more powerful, let's go for it and get it.

31
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:54,000
But the right hemisphere is seeing the whole picture, it has a sort of sustained, not a sort of sustained, it has sustained broad, vigilant attention to the whole.

32
00:05:54,000 --> 00:06:02,000
And it therefore sustains our sense of a whole to which we belong and where our position has meaning.

33
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:06,000
But we've decontextualized everything.

34
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:15,000
We now don't understand that a thing is not just a thing, it changes its nature depending on the context that it's in.

35
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:22,000
When we take it out of the context in which it belongs and from which it derives its meaning, it no longer seems to have any meaning.

36
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:32,000
So the trouble with this world picture is it sees meaningless items whose only possible value can come from ways in which we can use them.

37
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:48,000
And this has largely dominated, certainly in certain sectors, the way in which people now think of the natural world as a heap of resource which we can mine and use and exploit for effectively utilitarian purposes.

38
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:58,000
But the kind of attention that the right hemisphere is able to give sees a living web of interrelationships.

39
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:08,000
So it sees that nothing is just what it is outside of the context, but always is what it is because of the relations in which it stands for everything else.

40
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:17,000
And indeed, in the matter of things, I argue that relations are primary, they come before the relator, the things that are said to be related.

41
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:27,000
So they actually emerge out of a web of meaning, and that meaning is often implicit, whereas the left hemisphere doesn't understand what's not made explicit.

42
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:35,000
This is also a facet of our culture, that things have to be spelled out in language that, as it were, a machine could understand.

43
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:47,000
But in fact, almost everything that matters to us can't be subjected in this way to a translation or a degradation into everyday language.

44
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:55,000
And so if you ask me for examples, obviously poetry, when you explain a poem, you've somehow destroyed it.

45
00:07:56,000 --> 00:08:09,000
Although it's perfectly legitimate to pay that kind of attention to it for a while, but unless you re-embrace the whole with the new information, then you've lost something important.

46
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:21,000
But not just poetry, but obviously all the arts and music and painting and architecture, but also ritual, myth, narrative.

47
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:38,000
The ways in which we come to understand our place in the cosmos, which have always been very important, usually also involved with a story of the cosmos, a story about the superhuman, in other words, again, this sacred realm.

48
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:54,000
And I think all of this we lack to a large extent now. People are hungry for it, and when I speak to them about what has happened and show them, they immediately understand what's missing.

49
00:08:54,000 --> 00:09:04,000
But they often say things like, until I read you or until I heard you, I wasn't really aware of how much was missing from my world.

