171
00:27:09,000 --> 00:27:18,000
Well, I think again, beginning from the sense that we don't know it all is a very good place to start.

172
00:27:18,000 --> 00:27:24,000
I think the key feature of the way we think now is that it is hubristic.

173
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:31,000
In other words, it exemplifies an arrogant, overbearing sense that we know far more than we do.

174
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:39,000
And it not only is that disruptive of value and meaning, but it's also really not very intelligent.

175
00:27:39,000 --> 00:27:49,000
So if one can rekindle the sense of awe before things that are beautiful, before things in people that are genuinely good,

176
00:27:49,000 --> 00:27:59,000
and things that speak to us and therefore have a kind of truthfulness in the connection with us,

177
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:05,000
then we can begin to see a world that has much more meaning in it.

178
00:28:05,000 --> 00:28:16,000
But currently, beauty is curiously being neglected by almost everything, including art.

179
00:28:16,000 --> 00:28:22,000
A lot of modern art, the creator does not wish to be told that it's beautiful.

180
00:28:22,000 --> 00:28:24,000
They wish to be told that it's powerful.

181
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:29,000
And power, of course, is the only value recognised by the left hemisphere.

182
00:28:29,000 --> 00:28:34,000
But as Dostoevsky said, it's beauty that will save the world.

183
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:46,000
I puzzled over that for a long time because, of course, a sense of aesthetic value can lead one to be deceived.

184
00:28:46,000 --> 00:28:53,000
But then making wrong judgments about what's good and true can also lead you to deceive.

185
00:28:53,000 --> 00:29:00,000
But I think what he was getting at is that when we have really lost our bearings on truth and what is meant by goodness,

186
00:29:00,000 --> 00:29:06,000
so that now truth is whatever my truth is, we make it happen, there's no sense of it being,

187
00:29:06,000 --> 00:29:14,000
despite the fact that we, of course, I acknowledge and talk about this a lot, that we go to make parts of everything we experience.

188
00:29:14,000 --> 00:29:19,000
That doesn't mean that we just make it up, and it doesn't mean that some things are not sure of another,

189
00:29:19,000 --> 00:29:22,000
even though they may not be one single absolute truth.

190
00:29:22,000 --> 00:29:32,000
Goodness has been reduced to the following over a lot of rather mindless rules and ticking boxes for having expressed certain values or positions.

191
00:29:32,000 --> 00:29:35,000
And that, of course, has nothing really to do with goodness.

192
00:29:35,000 --> 00:29:42,000
But the one thing that can speak to us directly is beauty.

193
00:29:42,000 --> 00:29:54,000
And so in that state where we've been abandoned and felt lost by no particular bearings or goodness and truth, beauty can still call to us.

194
00:29:54,000 --> 00:29:57,000
And I think that's a good and important point.

195
00:29:57,000 --> 00:30:07,000
So I think all those three values, and they are, in my view, contributors to the sense of the sacred, their facets of the sacred,

196
00:30:07,000 --> 00:30:10,000
regaining that in our world I think is important.

197
00:30:10,000 --> 00:30:14,000
I'm not saying that everybody must suddenly start going to church or whatever.

198
00:30:14,000 --> 00:30:16,000
That's not my point.

199
00:30:16,000 --> 00:30:25,000
And I'd rather oppose to people who think that it's all in a book, whether that be a Christian book or a Muslim book or whatever.

200
00:30:25,000 --> 00:30:31,000
It's about a disposition of one's spirit, one's soul, towards the world.

201
00:30:31,000 --> 00:30:34,000
And what kind of a disposition is that?

202
00:30:34,000 --> 00:30:47,000
It's one in which there is room for awe and wonder, which helps us to see not that we're useless or meaningless but curiously that we have meaning and value.

203
00:30:47,000 --> 00:30:52,000
Because we're connected to something that is all inspiring that we know is bigger than us.

204
00:30:52,000 --> 00:31:00,000
But nonetheless, we're not humbled in the negative sense that we're made to feel small, although that might happen.

205
00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:04,000
We derive richness from that relationship.

206
00:31:04,000 --> 00:31:11,000
I think that's one thing, and I know we're to be the sense of compassion for things.

207
00:31:11,000 --> 00:31:25,000
And I think that's an important thing that's gone missing in our culture of anger, narcissistic rage, the heuristic belief that we are right and you must be wrong and so on.

208
00:31:25,000 --> 00:31:31,000
And a degree of modesty, basically.

209
00:31:31,000 --> 00:31:46,000
So I think those features, if we started adopting a more wondered, more modest and more compassionate view towards others, towards the world,

210
00:31:46,000 --> 00:31:51,000
I think a lot of our problems will begin to heal themselves.

211
00:31:51,000 --> 00:32:02,000
But as you know, in this world where people no longer feel there is any need or connection, mental illness is a colossal height.

212
00:32:02,000 --> 00:32:06,000
Most people think of themselves as basically lonely.

213
00:32:06,000 --> 00:32:15,000
And why? Because we have destroyed all the context in which people used to find their being and belonging.

214
00:32:15,000 --> 00:32:31,000
This idea that we're prevented from seeing these things, which has come through, to some extent, technology, technology is our ability to manipulate the world.

215
00:32:31,000 --> 00:32:34,000
It has removed us from it.

216
00:32:34,000 --> 00:32:40,000
And you might also say that we are kind of educated into it. We're given a value system.

217
00:32:40,000 --> 00:32:53,000
So as someone who's personally invested in the interest of education, I wonder what the principles might be of an education, if education is the way we create our own future,

218
00:32:53,000 --> 00:33:05,000
like on what kind of priorities and principles should it try and move forward?

219
00:33:05,000 --> 00:33:11,000
Well, it's only difficult to recapture things only in an educational system.

220
00:33:11,000 --> 00:33:22,000
Although an educational system can be very valuable and important, obviously, and I believe my own education was profoundly important in shaping me.

221
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:40,000
But I think things have to revalidate the importance of the family, that the way in which you think about the world, the things that you hope to be good and right,

222
00:33:40,000 --> 00:33:50,000
are part of what your family inculcates in you, by example, and sometimes by precept.

223
00:33:51,000 --> 00:34:06,000
As to schools, I think the first thing I'd say, because a lot of people imagine that the right hemisphere is a bit sort of let it all hang out, you know, this is sort of a hippie hemisphere.

224
00:34:06,000 --> 00:34:19,000
And that's how it was projected in the bad old days, when we used to say things like the left hemisphere is rational and verbal and the right hemisphere does pictures and gets emotional.

225
00:34:20,000 --> 00:34:30,000
The important point for here is that the right hemisphere is not only much better at feeling really the deep emotions rather than superficial social emotions.

226
00:34:30,000 --> 00:34:48,000
The ones preferred by the left hemisphere, anger, scorn, derision, a sense of self-pride, these are different from the deep emotions of togetherness, of sympathy, empathy.

227
00:34:48,000 --> 00:35:01,000
And so forth. But the right hemisphere is also the hemisphere of control of inappropriate or excessive emotion, which people perhaps didn't expect.

228
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:09,000
And what I'm leaning to here is that I don't think that education should just be a matter of do your own thing and let it all hang out.

229
00:35:09,000 --> 00:35:16,000
I think it's very important that there should be discipline. And discipline is now a sort of dirty word.

230
00:35:16,000 --> 00:35:30,000
But actually, the loss of self-discipline in our world, which has been eroded very badly in the last 50 years, with trades of self-indulgence, self-promotion, and so forth, over self-discipline.

231
00:35:31,000 --> 00:35:39,000
This will lead to tyranny, because if we don't discipline ourselves, then there's a need for external constraints on everything.

232
00:35:39,000 --> 00:35:58,000
And so you see an explosion of rules and algorithms and principles and handbooks and so on, which none of it should be necessary if people have any sensitivity to what is required of them through a morally cohesive society.

233
00:35:58,000 --> 00:36:13,000
So I think the sense that it's not all about us, it is about a society that we build to be proud of a society and its values, and as much as one recognizes what they are and agrees with them.

234
00:36:13,000 --> 00:36:23,000
But above all, to know more about humanities. I mean, the key is in the word. Without humanities, we don't really understand human beings.

235
00:36:23,000 --> 00:36:33,000
So it's very well to promote STEM subjects, which are the technical subjects, and I'm not saying they're not important at all.

236
00:36:33,000 --> 00:36:44,000
But like the left hemisphere not being unimportant, it is very important, it nonetheless needs to be set within a context of what the right hemisphere knows.

237
00:36:44,000 --> 00:36:56,000
And so all that technical information is only good if it's set in the context of a broader understanding of what human beings are and where we're going with our lives and with our society.

238
00:36:56,000 --> 00:37:06,000
And that will come from studying literature, history, music, drama. These things are not just add-ons, you know.

239
00:37:06,000 --> 00:37:19,000
These are the core in my view. And in the universities to begin with a thorough knowledge of Western civilization, beginning with the Greeks and the Romans and working forward.

240
00:37:19,000 --> 00:37:25,000
I expect nowadays somebody will say that it's exclusive or something, but I think it's extremely important.

241
00:37:25,000 --> 00:37:40,000
If you want to completely demoralize the people, tyrants have named this, destroy their history, cut them off from their history, and they will lose any will to defend themselves or anything else because they can't see any point anymore.

242
00:37:40,000 --> 00:37:55,000
So we really do need to stop being silly about this and accept that we are depriving young people of something very, very important unless we give them a proper grounding in their own culture.

243
00:37:55,000 --> 00:38:10,000
And that's not to say that it shouldn't include admiration for things that come from other cultures. I spent a lot of my life trying to emphasize the importance of Eastern values against those of the West.

244
00:38:10,000 --> 00:38:27,000
And it's only more recently that I realized that it's really important now with people taking, you know, Sledgehammers and pneumatic drills through Western culture to say, hang on, this is something completely amazing that we created.

245
00:38:27,000 --> 00:38:40,000
And you're using the freedom that it created, almost uniquely in the history of mankind, to destroy it. You have that liberty because of the very culture that you're against.

246
00:38:40,000 --> 00:38:56,000
So something absurd is happening in education now, and it involves reintroducing what is required. It's not that everybody must go on being educated, quote educated, up to university level.

247
00:38:56,000 --> 00:39:09,000
Some people will benefit from university and I'm sorry, some people won't. And when everybody has to go to university, then the universities themselves become less good places to learn.

248
00:39:09,000 --> 00:39:18,000
And I know this is all very unpopular, but it seems to me common sense actually. And there's a lot of people that don't want to be in school after a certain age.

249
00:39:18,000 --> 00:39:33,000
They become disruptive, pretty boys, and maybe the thing is to allow them to leave. And if they want to later, I think that universities should be a choice we make later when we've had a little bit of experience of life.

250
00:39:33,000 --> 00:39:40,000
And then if you really want to go to university, you've got a burning desire to know more about whatever, good, go for it.

251
00:39:40,000 --> 00:39:50,000
And better support such people in doing what they want to do, and that will make a better society and better universities to produce people that will make a better society.

252
00:39:50,000 --> 00:40:15,000
It sounds wise, I resonate with that. Something you kind of alluded to and have written at length about is purpose and a sense that we maybe have produced purpose to something extrinsic.

253
00:40:15,000 --> 00:40:35,000
It's instrumental. And lots of the most valuable stuff in life is intrinsically purposeful. And if we aim at, so I think you observed that we aim at happiness, and I would never call it measurably less happy, we aim at freedom and autonomy, but we're bound by restrictions and so on.

254
00:40:35,000 --> 00:40:48,000
So I guess those are kind of extrinsic purposes, arguably. How do we know what to aim at? Do you think that's right? How do we know what to aim at?

255
00:40:49,000 --> 00:40:53,000
Obviously in some ways this brings us to values again.

256
00:40:53,000 --> 00:40:54,000
Yes, yes.

257
00:40:54,000 --> 00:41:12,000
Because I see values as things that call to us from ahead. They may not be entirely resolved in the sense of brought into sharp focus for us, but they are entities that speak to us, that call to us. That is how I have experienced them.

258
00:41:12,000 --> 00:41:17,000
One is drawn forwards towards the good, the beautiful, the true.

259
00:41:17,000 --> 00:41:32,000
Now most of our images come from machines, and there's nothing more harmful than one can do. One can do it, then to try and approximate a human life to that of a machine, the functioning of a machine.

260
00:41:32,000 --> 00:41:46,000
So they are things that guide where we want to go from and front, whereas a machine is pushed from behind. A machine has no sense of direction. It's made to go in certain ways.

261
00:41:46,000 --> 00:41:59,000
When we come to talk about purpose, it's terribly important to distinguish between two kinds of purposes, and you did really allude to that when you said intrinsic, because machines have extrinsic purpose.

262
00:41:59,000 --> 00:42:09,000
In other words, the machine itself is not aware of a purpose. The machine is simply carrying out a purpose of the human being that made it.

263
00:42:09,000 --> 00:42:25,000
However, not everything has this utilitarian nature that is valued for it, and obviously examples are music and dance. These things are not valuable because they lead to us doing certain things.

264
00:42:25,000 --> 00:42:35,000
They are valuable because they have intrinsic meaning and value that speaks to us. They acquaint us with something that is beautiful and speaks to us.

265
00:42:35,000 --> 00:42:50,000
And that's what I mean by an intrinsic purpose. James Carrs, a philosopher, made a distinction between games that are infinite and games that are finite.

266
00:42:50,000 --> 00:43:02,000
So an example of an infinite game would be something like music, which doesn't reach a goal and then stop, but can be carried on for as long as people want to do it because its purpose is in itself.

267
00:43:03,000 --> 00:43:15,000
Finite games are done as a football game, so that we want an outcome out of a certain 90 minutes we have it and one team with one or the other.

268
00:43:15,000 --> 00:43:29,000
So that is a kind of distinction. And I suppose that what I'm very keen not to suggest is that if I say that I believe there is purpose in the cosmos and I think it's there,

269
00:43:29,000 --> 00:43:35,000
that I'm meaning it's put there by an engineering guard.

270
00:43:35,000 --> 00:43:53,000
So when you look at the cosmos, even the inanimate cosmos at large, or what we think is inanimate anyway, we see something that is constantly evolving, changing towards complexity and a kind of beauty.

271
00:43:53,000 --> 00:44:04,000
And there are drives, even in the inanimate world, inanimate structures have tendencies to go in certain directions.

272
00:44:04,000 --> 00:44:16,000
When it comes to life, much more so. So that's an important thing to realise, that there is a kind of direction.

273
00:44:17,000 --> 00:44:28,000
But it's not something that has been written in advance by the cosmos or by the ground of being or by God, whatever you want to call it.

274
00:44:28,000 --> 00:44:43,000
That doesn't mean to say it has no purpose, it has a direction towards certain values and the details as it were are absolutely open.

275
00:44:43,000 --> 00:44:49,000
So we're not, I believe, programmed to do every single thing we do.

276
00:44:49,000 --> 00:45:02,000
And I just don't believe and I can't believe that anyone now could possibly defend Laplace's 18th century vision that if you knew the position of momentum of every particle in the universe at a certain point,

277
00:45:02,000 --> 00:45:05,000
you wouldn't be able to unpack the whole of the rest of history.

278
00:45:05,000 --> 00:45:11,000
Surely modern physics already tells us that such certainty is not available.

279
00:45:11,000 --> 00:45:15,000
Now that doesn't mean to say that the only alternative is pure chaos.

280
00:45:15,000 --> 00:45:23,000
There is something very important in the dipole of order and disorder and that the important thing is that there should be both present.

281
00:45:23,000 --> 00:45:29,000
Without a bit of disorder the thing is dead and will sclerose and fossilise.

282
00:45:29,000 --> 00:45:40,000
It's that element of potential for change that is so important in everything, not just in the living world, but perhaps particularly obviously in the living world.

283
00:45:41,000 --> 00:45:48,000
And equally, of course, if there was only disorder and randomness, nothing would have any directional meaning.

284
00:45:48,000 --> 00:46:01,000
So I believe that we are and exemplify something that is purposeful but does not mean that I have no choice.

285
00:46:01,000 --> 00:46:06,000
I play it part and maybe I could expand on this a little.

286
00:46:06,000 --> 00:46:15,000
Because the really fascinating thing is why should there be life at all?

287
00:46:15,000 --> 00:46:20,000
It's a very expensive business life.

288
00:46:20,000 --> 00:46:25,000
It uses a great deal of energy, causes a lot of suffering,

289
00:46:25,000 --> 00:46:32,000
and it has to kick against the second law of thermodynamics,

290
00:46:32,000 --> 00:46:41,000
against the increase in entropy that suggests, because we are all the time moving against that trend.

291
00:46:41,000 --> 00:46:43,000
How could this have come about?

292
00:46:43,000 --> 00:46:56,000
I think the first thing to say about it is that to get over a phase in a process that would always stop any further progress because it was in itself disadvantageous,

293
00:46:56,000 --> 00:47:02,000
there has to be an ability for whatever it is to have a sense of something beyond.

294
00:47:02,000 --> 00:47:11,000
A very good point made by Bruce Charlton is that a simple one really but an important one.

295
00:47:11,000 --> 00:47:16,000
Why did sexual reproduction take hold?

296
00:47:16,000 --> 00:47:24,000
Originally organisms existed by parthenogenesis, in other words they divided, and that was it.

297
00:47:24,000 --> 00:47:37,000
The idea of having to find a suitable mate and only producing when you reproduce smaller numbers than you would get from being able to divide yourself

298
00:47:37,000 --> 00:47:44,000
means that you're perpetually in that early phase at a disadvantage in terms of competition.

299
00:47:44,000 --> 00:47:56,000
You're trying to do something that is uphill, and yet nonetheless somehow this has been brought into play and we carry on with that system.

300
00:47:56,000 --> 00:48:12,000
Another important point is that life gives us the capacity to respond to something beyond.

301
00:48:12,000 --> 00:48:18,000
Now that sounds a bit grand and vague but let me unpack it a bit.

302
00:48:18,000 --> 00:48:25,000
So inanimate things do respond to another inanimate thing.

303
00:48:25,000 --> 00:48:32,000
So we have periods of millions of years, rocks and dung get formed and move and change and so on.

304
00:48:32,000 --> 00:48:41,000
But their ability to respond to things is very limited for them to have in them, I suggest, consciousness.

305
00:48:41,000 --> 00:48:46,000
Though they exist in consciousness which is another matter.

306
00:48:46,000 --> 00:48:50,000
So what is it special about life that makes it worthwhile?

307
00:48:50,000 --> 00:49:05,000
I think it is actually the ability to respond to the values that are in the nature of the ground of being which are goodness, beauty and truth primarily.

308
00:49:06,000 --> 00:49:19,000
But those are the key elements and I think that it's the bringing about it of beings that can respond to them and therefore resonate with them and help them fulfil themselves and help further them.

309
00:49:19,000 --> 00:49:25,000
Or alternatively choose to ignore them and that's from right to do so, we have free agents.

310
00:49:25,000 --> 00:49:29,000
But I think that is why there is life, otherwise it's a great puzzle.

311
00:49:29,000 --> 00:49:39,000
As Ellen Whitehead said, there is very little survival in being alive, you last for a few years.

312
00:49:39,000 --> 00:49:43,000
But if you are inanimate you can persist for a very long time.

313
00:49:43,000 --> 00:49:48,000
So it can't be to do with creating creatures as a better and better at surviving.

314
00:49:48,000 --> 00:49:52,000
Because life itself is not a very good system for surviving.

315
00:49:52,000 --> 00:50:02,000
For the most ancient creatures, some examples of certain actinobacteria in the depths of the ocean, individual examples of them are a million years old.

316
00:50:02,000 --> 00:50:10,000
So everything that's happened since the evolution has been generally towards things becoming shorter lived.

317
00:50:10,000 --> 00:50:21,000
So how does one defend the difficulty of creating life, the problem with getting over the hump of entropy and the purpose of life?

318
00:50:21,000 --> 00:50:29,000
And I think that purpose is to be in the dynamic partnership of cosmos and creation.

319
00:50:29,000 --> 00:50:40,000
And Whitehead himself thought this, that the ground of being was ever more coming into being through, as it were, the dance of evolution with what it was bringing into being.

320
00:50:40,000 --> 00:50:49,000
So is that baked into evolution? Evolution is the algorithm that kind of explains developing towards complexity and life.

321
00:50:49,000 --> 00:50:55,000
But do you think baked into that is this ability to discern the given beautiful truth?

322
00:50:55,000 --> 00:50:59,000
Yes I do think so, that's right.

323
00:50:59,000 --> 00:51:16,000
I think another point that's relevant here is that until very recently we believe that evolution could only work by making billions and billions of false attempts until one happened by chance turned out to be helpful.

324
00:51:17,000 --> 00:51:32,000
A single cell can be faced with an assault for which it is not programmed by evolution, nor has experience in its own lifetime if you'd like to put it that way.

325
00:51:32,000 --> 00:51:42,000
It can make a change within a period of only a few days that if it had to happen by trial and error would take perhaps literally billions of years.

326
00:51:43,000 --> 00:52:01,000
So there is built into these adaptive changes is something that allows us to make changes much faster than a kind of blind, furrowing of the cars up in the air and hoping that the one that you want will land in your hand.

327
00:52:01,000 --> 00:52:10,000
That seems to be no longer a defensible position. I don't know why this is but it is the case anyway.

328
00:52:10,000 --> 00:52:15,000
One has to take that into account. So interesting how does that happen? I don't know.

329
00:52:15,000 --> 00:52:22,000
I think there are shapes, patterns if you like, that draw things towards themselves.

330
00:52:22,000 --> 00:52:42,000
And in fact, since we accomplished that wonderful feat of decoding the human genome, we've been made to realise how little information there is in the human genome, never near enough to deal with what a growing organism is faced with.

331
00:52:42,000 --> 00:52:57,000
And so there must be something else that allows forms and three dimensional shapes to be expressed that can't be expressed in the only 2% of DNA that actually gives information, instructional information.

332
00:52:57,000 --> 00:53:11,000
So where is that? And I think that people are beginning to see that there must be electromagnetic fields or fields of some kind that physics could recognise that contains information

333
00:53:11,000 --> 00:53:24,000
of a fish out of a form that something is moving towards. We see this in the evolution of creatures. If we interfere with their development, they will try to steer back to something.

334
00:53:24,000 --> 00:53:39,000
If you chop off the head of an hematode worm, it will end to regrow its head. And it will also, the new head will have the knowledge that the old head had, that that head has been incinerated.

335
00:53:39,000 --> 00:53:54,000
So where does it come from? When you cut off the antlers of a deer, every deer's antlers has a particular pattern, and it will produce the same pattern exactly that it has before, not the surrounding pattern.

336
00:53:54,000 --> 00:54:00,000
But where is that three dimensional pattern stored? I don't have the answer to that.

337
00:54:00,000 --> 00:54:15,000
I mean, what fascinating examples. You maybe think of, I think it's Simon Conway Morris, the paleozojous, who says that he points out that your evolution as an algorithm is very effective at describing these, but it doesn't describe something like music,

338
00:54:15,000 --> 00:54:25,000
you know, where whales and song cultures, birds of counterpoint and melody and harmony and so on. So it's more like mathematics, something you discover that is beautiful.

339
00:54:25,000 --> 00:54:36,000
And it brings to mind this idea that we are growing towards the beauty of the beautiful and the true that is part of the fabric of the universe.

340
00:54:36,000 --> 00:54:50,000
Yes, yes. I mean, quite how it works is it's not something I claim to understand. But I don't think that that's a reason for trying to conceal or deny things that are matters of observation.

341
00:54:50,000 --> 00:55:02,000
So there's something there that is shaping the course, the form, the nature of whatever it is that is coming into being.

342
00:55:03,000 --> 00:55:13,000
May I ask you about those people who probably sound somewhere significantly different to you, who think the world is making good progress.

343
00:55:14,000 --> 00:55:27,000
The late Hans Rosling or Stephen Pinker, who would say that. Actually, here's our hard data on longevity or literacy or healthcare.

344
00:55:27,000 --> 00:55:36,000
What we're doing is clearly moving in the right direction. It seems like you would like to say, we're actually not moving in the right direction.

345
00:55:36,000 --> 00:55:41,000
We need to back up and figure out where we've lost our way.

346
00:55:41,000 --> 00:55:54,000
I know you've actually corresponded a bit with Stephen Pinker. What's your response to the people who say we're making good progress and this is the right direction?

347
00:55:54,000 --> 00:56:01,000
Well, I think probably once again, it's a difference between the two illustrated by the difference between the hemispheres.

348
00:56:01,000 --> 00:56:12,000
So the left hemisphere would want to say that something was good by ticking certain boxes that it's beforehand decided are going to be important.

349
00:56:12,000 --> 00:56:23,000
So it finds, for example, that more people now earn a wage than in the past have did. So it says we're making progress.

350
00:56:23,000 --> 00:56:39,000
And one of the things I'd like to say about that is that the reason that there are more people who earn wages is that there has been massive erosion and destruction of the environment and ways of life of indigenous people

351
00:56:39,000 --> 00:56:49,000
who would be more or less forced to go to cities to try and get jobs, where of course they do get a pittance, but they are for the first time truly poor.

352
00:56:49,000 --> 00:56:59,000
We know that levels of human flourishing, in other words, a sense of wellbeing, a sense of belonging, a sense of happiness, a sense of fulfillment,

353
00:56:59,000 --> 00:57:07,000
these things are much higher in pre-modern Western societies than they are in such societies.

354
00:57:07,000 --> 00:57:17,000
And that as people move into such societies, as unfortunately they do all the time, they become progressively more unhappy.

355
00:57:17,000 --> 00:57:35,000
And one of the fascinating findings is that poor Mexicans who move to America, in the first generation of those who go there, their rates of mental illness are relatively low compared with the Native American population.

356
00:57:35,000 --> 00:57:48,000
But in the next generation they become considerably higher, and in the generation after that they approximate to the levels of misery that are typical of the US population.

357
00:57:48,000 --> 00:57:54,000
Now it seems to me that you can only argue that this is a better society by chance.

358
00:57:55,000 --> 00:58:09,000
One of the things that strikes me about your work in is that you are taken in by people who have pretty different worlds.

359
00:58:09,000 --> 00:58:19,000
They might be fairly Eastern, very Christian, or not religious at all, and to some extent they put a flag in your technique,

360
00:58:19,000 --> 00:58:23,000
and he's like, what are you saying is something we resonate with?

361
00:58:23,000 --> 00:58:37,000
So if you have a Venn diagram of these different perspectives with you in the middle, what is it that you think you're putting your finger on that they all resonate with?

362
00:58:37,000 --> 00:58:51,000
I think that what a lot of people say when they write to me, and God bless them, a lot of do saying that my writing has changed their lives, or even saved their lives and so on, which is a remarkable and wonderful thing.

363
00:58:51,000 --> 00:59:10,000
The common thing they say is, there was a lot of this that I knew at some level, and I understood at some level, but had no words to express, and what you've done is to enable me to see why believing those things and knowing those things is important.

364
00:59:10,000 --> 00:59:34,000
And so I think what I've done is to bring things that are very hard to express, and are pitfalls and traps everywhere, in trying to express them to a point where people can read them and get them, even if they don't begin from that standpoint of understanding what it is I'm trying to unfold.

365
00:59:34,000 --> 00:59:54,000
So I see my work as taking people on a journey to say, look at this, and let's have a look at this, and there's a good bit coming in an hour or two when we see a beautiful view, and then leading them to a position where their view of the world is quite different than the one they started off with.

366
00:59:54,000 --> 01:00:21,000
And they're not forced to accept it, of course, I'm sure some people don't, but pleasingly a lot of people do, and so I think that is opening people's eyes to the value of imagination and of intuition, as well as science and reason, which I find myself championing a lot these days, because they're also under attack from people who don't like science and reason,

367
01:00:21,000 --> 01:00:42,000
because they might show the things that they believe to be, you know, poorly evidenced. So I think it's that, and I think I hope, giving people hope, and giving them some sense that there is meaning and beauty and purpose there to discover.

368
01:00:43,000 --> 01:00:56,000
But, you know, you have to have skin in the game, as it were, you can't sort of sit there and expect it to go plump into your lap, you have to make choices and you have to strive a little for those things.

369
01:00:57,000 --> 01:01:11,000
I don't mean that sort of compete, but you need to sort of have a degree of conviction and determination to follow a path. And, you know, following through on something is quite important.

370
01:01:11,000 --> 01:01:31,000
One thing that I come to realise rather late in life, that actually following through something, even though it may take you through a viewpoint where you have to change, and it should take you through a viewpoint where you have to change, is rather important.

371
01:01:31,000 --> 01:01:36,000
If you're not sure when you don't like what's coming next.

372
01:01:36,000 --> 01:01:39,000
Like you say, creativity requires resistance.

373
01:01:39,000 --> 01:01:41,000
It requires resistance.

374
01:01:41,000 --> 01:01:53,000
And growth, I think it was, I heard you point out in previous talk about that fascinating fact that trees, the grow into like a bio-do, never develop the internal strength because the resistance of wind isn't there.

375
01:01:53,000 --> 01:01:54,000
That's right.

376
01:01:54,000 --> 01:01:55,000
And I love that as a metaphor.

377
01:01:55,000 --> 01:02:03,000
The biologists couldn't understand why are all these mature trees protected from every kind of heart? Why are they all falling over before they reach full maturity?

378
01:02:03,000 --> 01:02:08,000
And the answer is they had nothing to resist and trees actually thrive on wind.

379
01:02:08,000 --> 01:02:11,000
It's nice testing the wood and building the wood.

380
01:02:11,000 --> 01:02:18,000
It's a beautiful metaphor for why life is not supposed to be a walk in the park.

381
01:02:18,000 --> 01:02:23,000
It's not supposed to be just a matter of enjoyment.

382
01:02:23,000 --> 01:02:27,000
In fact, that would be extremely disappointing.

383
01:02:27,000 --> 01:02:38,000
I don't want to do a spoiler for people who haven't read the history of the world in ten and a half chapters, but maybe I will anyway.

384
01:02:38,000 --> 01:02:55,000
It's a wonderful clever book and at the end of it, there was a story about somebody waking up in a hospital and a very beautiful nurse is bringing lots of things to eat.

385
01:02:55,000 --> 01:02:58,000
And the person said, where am I?

386
01:02:58,000 --> 01:03:05,000
And in the insuring conversation, it turns out that he's tied and he is in fact in heaven.

387
01:03:05,000 --> 01:03:10,000
And he said, what am I supposed to do? You can do anything you like.

388
01:03:10,000 --> 01:03:14,000
If you're a keen golfer, you can have a round of golf with kept nipples.

389
01:03:14,000 --> 01:03:18,000
Whatever it is that you want to do, you can do it.

390
01:03:18,000 --> 01:03:27,000
And he sort of thinks about this as a long conversation and he says, do people tend to stay up here?

391
01:03:27,000 --> 01:03:33,000
And he says, no, usually after about 300 years they're asked to go back.

392
01:03:33,000 --> 01:03:42,000
I just thought that was such a brilliant insight that actually we're not happiest when just everything is given to us.

393
01:03:42,000 --> 01:03:50,000
There's something to be said for having to put oneself out to encounter resistance or overcome resistance and it helps one grow.

394
01:03:50,000 --> 01:03:59,000
You're thinking of a very person in problem because technology has made life far too convenient.

395
01:03:59,000 --> 01:04:11,000
There's not enough resistance and the texture of life feels different if you can breeze through it.

396
01:04:11,000 --> 01:04:21,000
Yes, apparently architects have been asked to design shocking sensors with steps and things so that people actually do have to exert themselves.

397
01:04:21,000 --> 01:04:27,000
And it's healthier than being whisked everywhere in lifts and on moving.

398
01:04:27,000 --> 01:04:33,000
Yeah, of course the consequences in your body are not insignificant to climb stairs.

399
01:04:33,000 --> 01:04:39,000
Where do you find hope in the best case scenario?

400
01:04:39,000 --> 01:04:44,000
When you look at the world and you see things are not going too well,

401
01:04:44,000 --> 01:04:52,000
things are not being made in the interests of the planet or the people in it.

402
01:04:52,000 --> 01:04:58,000
But at the same time you get letters, you give talks, you inspire people to think differently.

403
01:04:58,000 --> 01:05:06,000
Where do you find, I suppose, hope and what are going to be the engines of change?

404
01:05:06,000 --> 01:05:14,000
Well, I think the answer to those two questions come together.

405
01:05:14,000 --> 01:05:22,000
First of all, although things don't look as though they're getting better, it's a fool who predicts the future.

406
01:05:22,000 --> 01:05:30,000
I don't know what's in store and therefore there is always room for hope and I think one has a duty in a way to hope

407
01:05:30,000 --> 01:05:36,000
because otherwise we'd all just give up and then certainly everything would collapse.

408
01:05:36,000 --> 01:05:45,000
But there is really grounds for hope in the very people who are going to have to be the agents of change,

409
01:05:45,000 --> 01:05:49,000
namely young people.

410
01:05:49,000 --> 01:06:02,000
And in just the last couple of months I gave lectures, public lectures in Oxford and Cambridge

411
01:06:02,000 --> 01:06:08,000
and then in America in three or four different places.

412
01:06:08,000 --> 01:06:17,000
And once I came away with was an overwhelming sense of how good and decent a lot of young people are

413
01:06:17,000 --> 01:06:29,000
and they can be caricatured, the worst of them can be caricatured as having sort of righteous slogans about what must happen.

414
01:06:29,000 --> 01:06:43,000
But the people I met were appropriately less arrogant, less know-it-all, delightful, responsive, creative, imaginative

415
01:06:43,000 --> 01:07:00,000
and committed to trying to understand things and make them better and not just follow whatever rules were being laid down for them by the current media kind of pundits.

416
01:07:00,000 --> 01:07:10,000
So I thought there is a great deal of hope here and it really was lovely for me and for them to say that they really resonated with what I was saying.

417
01:07:11,000 --> 01:07:14,000
And so that was very strong.

418
01:07:14,000 --> 01:07:18,000
There is a piece of experience, right, which is the right hemisphere.

419
01:07:18,000 --> 01:07:21,000
Yes, absolutely.

420
01:07:21,000 --> 01:07:23,000
So there we are.

421
01:07:23,000 --> 01:07:37,000
So if I pull the threads together, I've asked you, well, we've got to know all over the place because there's so much in your thinking that it seems to connect to this question of what are cultures preventing us from seeing.

422
01:07:37,000 --> 01:08:03,000
And it seems like if you take that characterisation of the left hemisphere as utilitarian, understanding values of your utility of pleasure but little else, and that's shaped the way we're attending and the purposes we're finding to great injury to the way that we're living and to the planet we're living in and so on.

423
01:08:04,000 --> 01:08:19,000
And so to discover the answer to what are like cultures preventing us from seeing means listening more keenly to discern what is good and true and beautiful.

424
01:08:19,000 --> 01:08:28,000
Would that be one kind of summary of how we attend better to what it is we're not seeing?

425
01:08:28,000 --> 01:08:32,000
Yes, I think the first thing is being aware of what it is one isn't seeing.

426
01:08:32,000 --> 01:08:36,000
Because unless you have that knowledge, you won't make the effort, of course.

427
01:08:36,000 --> 01:08:48,000
So the first thing is to get people to a place where they experience some of the things that would give them a sense of something beyond what it is they so cleverly already know.

428
01:08:49,000 --> 01:09:01,000
The business of education is not about confirming the prejudice that you come into education with about shaking your prejudices and by enabling you to see another point of view.

429
01:09:01,000 --> 01:09:13,000
And so I always say that in education, it should be part of the business to teach people to argue for different points of view.

430
01:09:14,000 --> 01:09:22,000
And so I could make an argument against myself before positions I may have stated in this interview.

431
01:09:22,000 --> 01:09:32,000
But I think it's important to be able to do that and not to think that everybody who thinks differently for you must be criminal or stupid.

432
01:09:32,000 --> 01:09:38,000
But they may have something there that is worth hearing and that there may be things that it's worth trying to experience.

433
01:09:38,000 --> 01:09:56,000
I think reconnecting spending more time in nature and trying to bring yourself to be part of a group of people whose values you respect and spending some time with them.

434
01:09:56,000 --> 01:10:07,000
And if possible spending time in spiritual practices, which may be conventional or unconventional, but they're better than none.

435
01:10:07,000 --> 01:10:16,000
These things are at least orientating us to the idea that what we know is not at all. It's not the whole story.

436
01:10:16,000 --> 01:10:20,000
And whatever that whole story is, we will never know it in full.

437
01:10:20,000 --> 01:10:32,000
But it is part of the business of life to try and take ourselves on that journey towards a fuller understanding of who we are.

438
01:10:33,000 --> 01:10:35,000
That was a wonderful lift.

439
01:10:35,000 --> 01:10:38,000
Ian, thank you so much for your time.

440
01:10:38,000 --> 01:10:40,000
Thanks for being so generous with your thoughts.

441
01:10:40,000 --> 01:10:42,000
Thank you very much indeed.

